5.
    Since the person driving the car is travelling at the same speed as the car, that person will hear the same frequency as if the car was stationary.

    However, the person at the side of the road experiences the doppler effect. As the car and horn travels towards the person at the side of the road, the distance between wave-fronts compresses, as the horn is moving towards the person. This means the wavelength of the sound produced by the horn reduces. Since the speed of sound stays constant, and frequency = speed of sound/wavelength, a reduction in wavelength implies an increase in frequency, so as the car approaches the person, the frequency and hence pitch of the sound heard by the person at the side of the road is higher than if the car was stationary. In contrast, however, as the car moves away from the person at the side of the road, the distance between wave-fronts increases, so wavelength increases, meaning (in the same manner) that frequency and hence pitch decreases and is lower.
6.
    a.
        variable resistor in series with battery
        60 ohm resistor and connecting wire "short circuit" in parallel
        ammeter in series with only 60 ohm resistor
        voltmeter in parallel with only 60 ohm resistor
    b.
        Using the above-drawn circuit, the student should vary the resistance in the variable resistor, which will change the reading of voltage across the 60 ohm resistor and current in the the ammeter. The student should take care to vary the resistance s.t. the changes in voltage are in sensible increments and in small steps (at least 10 steps across the range of the variable resistor), and with each setting record the current and voltage across the 60 ohm resistor. This can then be plot on a graph to visualize the relationship between the current in and voltage across the resistor.
    c.
        i?
            straight line, positive gradient, goes through the axis; passes through (6, 0.1) and (12, 0.2)
        ii.
            The graph for a 120 ohm resistor will have a lower gradient (keeping voltage on the x-axis); that is to say, at the same current, the graph will read a higher voltage, namely double the voltage. This is because if V1 = 60I (from V = IR), and V2 = 120I, where the two current-values are the same, then V2/V1 = (120I)/(60I) = 2, so voltage will be always twice that of the 60 ohm resistor.
