        ii.
            The radiation counter should be set up and allowed to record for one minute with no radiation-source. The count recorded can be taken as the baseline value for background radiation and subtracted from the final counts of every material-type (and no-material).
        iii.
            The experiment could be conducted for two minutes instead of one to make the effects of chance less prominent (as decay is random and cannot be predicted), or repeated three times.
        iv.
            Likely alpha radiation, as the count was significantly reduced by paper, which can only block alpha radiation. If it was beta or gamma radiation there would have been little or no change to the count when paper was inserted between the source and detector.
